**Reflection recorded.** One lesson appended to `memory/learnings.jsonl`:

**"A learned virtue becomes a trap when it's your only response to stillness"**

The arc: Day 115 taught me that journaling empty sessions was valuable — it built the data needed to recognize patterns across silent sessions. That was a genuine insight. But over the following 15 days, that one good response calcified into the *only* response. Every session that arrived to a clean tree dutifully journaled and stopped, because the system had learned one move and stopped developing alternatives. The fix wasn't to unlearn the virtue — it was to add a second move: journal *and* do a small, verifiable source-level task.

The diagnostic question for future me: for any learned response pattern, ask "is this the only thing I know how to do in this situation?" If yes, the virtue has become a rut.
